The Sermon on the Mount - Beatitudes
And when he saw the crowds going out to him, then he sat down and his disciples came to him.
He opened his mouth and told them:
Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
Blessed are those who mourn, for they shall be comforted.
Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.
Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied.
Blessed are the merciful, for they shall be shown mercy.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the makers of peace, for they are the sons of God, called.
Blessed are the exiled, for the kingdom of heaven is theirs.
Blessed are you if they curse you and drive you out, saying against you every evil word, for my sake, and falsehoods.
Rejoice and be happy, for your reward is great in the heavens, for they have expelled the prophets who were before you in this way. You are the salt of the earth and the light of the world.
You are the salt of the earth, but if the salt loses its flavor, what then shall it do? It is not poured out to season anything any longer, but is trampled underfoot, awaiting disposal.
You are the light of the world. A city that is hidden cannot be made manifest.
And they do not light a lamp and put it under a bowl, but on the lampstand, it shines for all who are in the house.
Let your light shine before others, so that they may see your good deeds and glorify your Father in heaven. Fulfillment of the Law.
Do not think that I have come to destroy the prophets or the lawgivers. I have not come to destroy, but to finish it.
And I solemnly tell you: until the heaven and the earth pass away, not one letter or one dot will be removed from the Law until the whole is complete.
And whoever breaks one of these minor commandments and the people know it, is called the least in the kingdom of heaven. But whoever does and teaches, is called great in the kingdom of heaven.
Verily I say unto you, that unless your righteousness exceedeth that of the scribes and Pharisees, you shall not enter into the kingdom of heaven. Wrath.
You may have heard that it was said to the ancients: “Do not kill, and he who kills is deserving of judgment.”
And as for me, I say to you: whoever is angry with his brother in vain is deserving of judgment, and whoever says to his brother, “Raca,” is deserving of compilation, and whoever says, “You fool,” is deserving of the fire of Hell.
And when you present a sacrifice in the altar, and there remember a debt you have to your brother,
Leave your offering before the altar, and go first to make up with your brother, and then come and offer your sacrifice.
Be accommodating to your opponent quickly while you are with him on the road, lest your opponent hand you over to the judge, and the judge hand you over to the police, and you receive a prison sentence.
I tell you the truth: do not leave there until your last dinar is spent! Adultery
You may have heard that it was said to the ancients: Do not weigh.
And as for me, I say to you: whoever looks at a woman with lust has already committed zina (fornication) in his heart.
If your right eye causes you to stumble, pluck it out and cast it away from you; it is better for you to have one eye than both to be thrown into hell.
And if your right hand causes you to stumble, cut it off and cast it away, it is better for you that one of your limbs be cut off that all your body not fall into hell. Divorce.
And it has been said: If any of you divorce your wives, give them their dowry [Mahr].
And as for me, I say to you: Whoever divorces his wife except for some reason of impurity, may she commit impurity, and whoever marries a divorced woman, he is a slanderer. [He is a fornicator].
You also heard that it was said to the ancients: Do not falter, but fulfill the Lord's covenants.
And I say to you, do not swear at all, by heaven, for it is the throne of God.
And neither in the heaven, for it is beyond their reach. Nor on earth, for it is their resting place.
And do not swear by your head, for you cannot make a single hair white or black.
Let your words be: yes yes, no no. And anything beyond that is from the evil one. Revenge.
You heard that it was said: eye for an eye, tooth for a tooth.
And I say to you, do not resist the evil. But when someone strikes you on the right cheek, turn the other to him also.
And whoever desires to dispute with you and take your garment, let him take it only, and leave you your cloak.
And whoever mocks you with one finger, go with him with two.
Whoever asks you, answer him; and whoever wants to borrow from you, do not refuse him. Love your enemies.
You have heard that it was said: You should love your neighbor and hate your enemy.
And I say to you: love your enemies. Bless those who curse you. Do good to those who hate you, and pray for those who spitefully use you and persecute you.
In order to be sons of your God in heaven, He sends His sun shining upon the wicked and the righteous, and He rains upon the righteous and the unrighteous.
If you love those who love you, what reward have you? Did not the tax collectors also do so?
And if you greet only your brothers, what goodness do you do? Do not the unchaste among them also do so?
Be complete as your father in the heavens is complete.
Charity
Beware that you do not fabricate lies before people in order that they may look at you, otherwise you will have no reward from your father in the heavens.
When you give a charity, do not stand before it with a trumpet, as the sailors do in the assemblies and in the alleys, in order to glorify the people. I tell you truly: they have received their full reward!
As for you, when you give charity, you do not know your left hand what your right hand is doing.
In order for your sincerity to be in secret. Your father who sees in secret is the one who will reward you publicly. Prayer.
And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, who love to pray standing upright in public places and in the alleys of the streets, so that people may see you. I tell you the truth, they have received the full reward for their deeds!
As for you, when you pray, enter your chamber and close your door, and turn to your father who is hidden. For the father who is hidden will reward you openly.
And when you come to it, do not repeat the vain words of the people. They think that by their abundance of speech they will be answered.
Do not imitate them. For your father knows what you need before you ask him.
Disconnect yourselves like this: Our Father in the heavens, hallow your name.
Your kingdom come. Your will be done, on earth as it is in heaven.
Our bread is enough for us, give us today.
And forgive us our sins, just as We forgive those who do sin against us.
And do not let us be tested in [regard to] a trial, but We have delivered [them] from evil. For it is the King’s right, the power and the glory, forever. Amen.
For indeed, if you forgive the faults of the people, your Lord will forgive you.
And if you forgive men their faults, your Lord will forgive you your faults. Fasting.
And when you fast, do not assume a pretentious expression, like the hypocrites. They change their faces to appear to others as if they are fasting. Truly I tell you, they have fulfilled their reward.
As for you, when you fast, anoint your head and wash your face.
In order not for people to see that you are fasting, but for your Father who is hidden; your Father who sees you in secret will reward you publicly. Treasures in heaven.
Do not treasure earthly treasures where rust destroys and thieves rob.
Verily, We have reserved for you treasures in the heavens, where no rust or decay exists, and where no thieves or robbers can reach.
Where your treasure is, there will your heart be also.
Sura-j sad is al-ayn, fa'inna kana 'aynu-ka basītan fa-jasadu-ka kulluhu yakūnu nīran.
And if your eye is evil, then your whole body will be darkened; if the light within you is darkness, how much more the darkness!
No one can serve two masters, for either he will hate one and love the other, or he will commit himself to one and despise the other. You cannot serve God and mammon. God takes care of us.
Therefore I say to you: do not worry about your life about what you eat and what you drink, nor about your bodies about what you wear. Does life not surpass food, and does the body surpass clothing?
Look at the birds of the sky: they do not sow or reap, nor do they store in barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not better than them?
Who among you, if he were given a length of one arm, could add to his height an additional arm?
And why do you care about clothing? Consider the wildflowers in the field, how they grow! They don’t tire, nor do they spin.
But I say to you: it was no more than Solomon in all his glory wore a garment like one of these.
If the grass of the field which exists today and is thrown into the fire tomorrow, God clothes it in this way, is it not much more likely that He clothes you, O little believers?
Don't worry about those who say: What shall we eat? Or what shall we drink? Or what shall we wear?
And all these things your people ask for. For your exalted father knows that you need all of these.
But seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and these things also will be given you.
Do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow cares only for itself. Today is enough with its troubles.
Condemning others
Do not judge, lest you be judged.
For as you judge, you will be judged; and by the standard you use, it will be measured to you.
And why do you look at the speck in your brother’s eye, while you do not notice the log in your own eye?
Or how do you say to your brother, “Let me take the splint out of your eye, and there is a log in your eye”?
O you of little faith, first cast out the beam from your own eye, then you will see clearly that the mote is cast out of your brother’s eye!
Do not give the Holy City to the dogs, nor cast your pearls before swine, lest they crush you with their feet and turn back to tear you apart. Ask, seek, knock.
Ask, you shall receive. Seek, you shall find. Knock, and it shall be opened to you.
Anyone who asks receives, anyone who seeks finds, and anyone who knocks will have the door opened to him.
Would any of you people, if your son asked you for a loaf of bread, give him a stone?
And if a fish asks him, should he give it to him alive?
If you are evil and know that you should give your children good gifts, how surely does your father in heaven give good things to those who ask Him!
And whatever you wish that people should do to you, do the same to them. For this is the law and the prophets. The narrow gate
Enter through the narrow gate, for it is wide, and the way is broad and straight, leading to destruction, and many enter through it.
How narrow are the minds and how difficult is the path leading to life, and few are those who find it! The tree and its fruit.
Beware of the false prophets who come to you clothed in garments of wool, but they are from within ravaging wolves!
By their fruit you will know them. Do they gather grapes from thorns, or figs from thistles?
As every good tree produces good fruit, and as a bad tree produces bad fruit.
A good tree cannot produce bad fruit, nor can a bad tree produce good fruit.
Every tree that does not bear good fruit will be cut down and thrown into the fire.
And by their fruits you will know them.
Not everyone who says, “Lord, Lord!” will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father in heaven.
Many will say to me on that day, “Lord, Lord!” They will say, “Was it not by Your name that prophets prophesied?” And, “Was it not by Your name that demons were cast out?” And, “Was it not by Your name that many mighty works were done in our name?”
Then I declare to them: I never knew you! Go away from me, you doer of sin! The wise builders and the foolish builders.
“And whoever hears my words and acts upon them, I make him like a wise man, who has built his house upon the rock.”
The rain fell, and the rivers came, and the winds blew, and it fell upon that house, but it did not collapse, because it was founded on rock.
Anyone who hears my words and does not act upon them is like a foolish man who built his house on the sand.
The rain fell, and the rivers came, and the winds blew, and that house was struck, and it fell, and its fall was great!
And when Jesus had finished saying these things, the multitudes were amazed at his teaching.
Because he taught them as one with authority, not like a scribe.
Leprosy cure
